The '''dharni''' ({{lang-ne|धार्नि|translit=dhārni}}) is an obsolete [[Units of measurement|unit]] of [[mass]], formerly used in [[Nepal]], of about {{frac|2|1|2}}&nbsp;[[seer (unit)|seer]]. It was divided into 2&nbsp;[[bisauli (unit)|bisauli]] (बिसौलि), 4&nbsp;[[Bori (unit)|boṛi]] (बोड़ि), or 12&nbsp;[[Pao (unit)|pāu]] (पाउ).<ref name="Turner">{{citation | last = Turner | first = Ralph Lilley | authorlink = Ralph Lilley Turner | title = A comparative and etymological dictionary of the Nepali language | url = http://dsal.uchicago.edu/dictionaries/turner/ | location = London | publisher = K.&nbsp;Paul, Trench, Trubner | year = 1931 | page = 328}}.</ref> The [[United Nations]] Statistical Office gave an approximate equivalence of 2.3325&nbsp;[[kilogram]]s (5.142&nbsp;[[Pound (mass)|pounds]] [[avoirdupois]]) in 1966.<ref name="UN">{{citation | author = Statistical Office of the United Nations | title = World Weights and Measures. Handbook for Statisticians | id = ST/STAT/SER.M/21/Rev.1 | location = New York | publisher = United Nations | year = 1966}}.</ref>
